{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}}
{{Use Australian English|date=November 2016}}
{{Infobox organization
| name   = Healthy Skepticism Inc
| founded_date      = 1983
| founder           = Peter R. Mansfield
| Non-profit_slogan = Improving health by reducing harm from misleading drug promotion
| homepage          = http://www.healthyskepticism.org
}}
'''Healthy Skepticism Inc''' is an international [[non-profit organisation]] whose main aim is to "improve health by reducing harm from misleading [[drug promotion]]".

Healthy Skepticism was founded in 1983 with the name Medical Lobby for Appropriate Marketing (MaLAM). It was begun by an [[Australia]]n medical student, Peter R. Mansfield,  who had the idea for the organization during his final year elective in [[Bangladesh]] in 1982. MaLAM initially focused on campaigning against questionable [[marketing]] practices in [[developing countries]]. These included the promotion of [[appetite]] stimulants, tonics and [[anabolic steroid]]s to parents of malnourished children. MaLAM was modelled on [[Amnesty International]] and wrote open letters to the international headquarters of [[pharmaceutical companies]] questioning them about specific advertisements. MaLAM letters were signed by supporters around the world and contributed to many improvements in drug marketing, several products being removed from the market and many [[advertising]] claims changed.<ref name="pmid12457804">{{cite journal |author=Dukes MN |title=Accountability of the pharmaceutical industry |journal=[[The Lancet|Lancet]] |volume=360 |issue=9346 |pages=1682–4 |date=November 2002 |pmid=12457804 |doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(02)11599-6 |url=http://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S0140-6736(02)11599-6}}</ref><ref name="pmid2573769">{{cite journal |vauthors=Wade VA, Mansfield PR, McDonald PJ |title=Drug companies' evidence to justify advertising |journal=[[The Lancet|Lancet]] |volume=2 |issue=8674 |pages=1261–3 |date=November 1989 |pmid=2573769 |doi= 10.1016/S0140-6736(89)91862-X|url=http://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S0140-6736(89)91862-X}}</ref><ref>Cullen, W.R. (2008) "Is Arsenic an Aphrodisiac?: The Sociochemistry of an Element" London: Royal Society of Chemistry (Great Britain) p. 19 [https://books.google.com/books?id=yyaTdY4UGLMC&pg=PA19&lpg=PA19&dq=bayers+tonic+pakistan&source=bl&ots=QaqgPKnwJF&sig=qZ9qem6TzXTlzypkIHNyh6ezYZ8&hl=en&ei=v2EOSpO-CMeBkQWt052kBA&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2]</ref> MaLAM reported more than 450 alleged violations of the voluntary code of conduct of the drug industry in 1987,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=19910611&slug=1288354 |title=Dangerous Exports -- Drugs Banned In The U.S. Find Overseas Markets |date=11 June 1991 |work=[[Seattle Times]] |author=Christopher Scanlan}}</ref> and also questioned drug advertisements in Australia during 1993 to 1997 with funding from the Australian federal government.

In 2001, the organisation’s name was changed to Healthy Skepticism and its work widened to include [[research]], [[education]] and [[advocacy]] about misleading drug promotion in all countries. It has concentrated recently on raising awareness amongst [[health professional]]s of the influence that marketing techniques have on their decisions, and the psychological factors which make them vulnerable to that influence.<ref name="pmid17090212">See, for example: {{cite journal |vauthors=Mansfield PR, Lexchin J, Wen LS, Grandori L, McCoy CP, Hoffman JR, Ramos J, Jureidini JN |title=Educating health professionals about drug and device promotion: advocates' recommendations |journal=[[PLoS Med.]] |volume=3 |issue=11 |pages=e451 |date=November 2006 |pmid=17090212 |pmc=1630716 |doi=10.1371/journal.pmed.0030451 |url=http://medicine.plosjournals.org/perlserv/?request=get-document&doi=10.1371/journal.pmed.0030451 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071106095923/http://medicine.plosjournals.org/perlserv/?request=get-document&doi=10.1371%2Fjournal.pmed.0030451 |archivedate=6 November 2007 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

